Azure Storage provides 
a REST API to work with the containers and data stored in each account. 
use Client library

Security
RBAC - best for blobs & queues
Access keys - for in-house trusted applications
Shared Access Signature - For untrusted clients, use a shared access signature (SAS).
Types of shared access signatures:
 a service-level SAS 
 an account-level SAS
 
 Authorization is supported by a public preview of Azure Active Directory credentials (for blobs and queues), 
 a valid account access key, or a shared access signature (SAS) token.
 
 Control network access to your storage account:
 By default, storage accounts accept connections from clients on any network. 
 You can restrict access to specific IP addresses, ranges, or virtual networks.
 
 Azure Storage Account > Networking > All Networks | Selected Networks
 
 Azure Defender for Storage
 Azure Defender for Storage is currently available for Blob storage, Azure Files, and Azure Data Lake Storage Gen2.


cross-origin resource sharing (CORS)





